> If you can't get enough of Korean-inspired flavors, this meal is sure to
> leave you satisfied. The dish centers around savory-sweet bulgogi sauce,
> whisked with a bit of butter and spooned over succulent pork chops.
> There's also a gingery stir-fry of bok choy, cabbage, and carrots on the
> side. Yeah, this meal has a little bit of something for everyone.

Wash and dry all produce.

Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Trim and
peel @carrot{3%oz}; grate on the largest holes of a #box grater{}. Peel and
mince or grate @ginger{1%thumb} until you have 1 tsp (2 tsp for 4 servings).
Zest and quarter @lime{1}.

Pat @pork chops{12%oz} dry with #paper towels{}; season all over with @salt{}
and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tbsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat.
Add pork and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes} per side.
> TIP: If crust begins to brown too quickly, reduce heat to medium.

Turn off heat; transfer pork to a #cutting board{}. Wipe out pan.

Melt @butter{1%tbsp} in same pan over medium-high heat. Add scallion whites;
cook until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in @bulgogi sauce{4%oz} and 1 TBSP water. Bring to a simmer and cook,
stirring, until warmed through, ~{2-3%minutes}. Turn off heat.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tbsp} in a second large pan over
medium-high heat. Add carrot, @bok choy and napa cabbage{4%oz}, and
@shredded red cabbage{4%oz}. Cook, stirring occasionally, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add minced ginger; cook, stirring frequently, until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in lime zest and juice from one lime wedge (two wedges for 4 servings).
Season with salt and pepper. Remove from heat.

Slice pork crosswise.

Divide veggie stir-fry between plates and top with pork. Drizzle pork with
sauce. Sprinkle with scallion greens and @sesame seeds{1%tbsp}. Squeeze juice
from remaining lime wedges over everything and serve.